            <blockquote>
                <p>
                    At any given daylight moment across America, approximately 660,000
                    drivers are using cell phones or manipulating electronic devices while
                    driving, a number that has held steady since 2010.
                </p>
                <footer>http://www-nrd.nhtsa.dot.gov/Pubs/811719.pdf</footer>
            </blockquote>
            <br />
            <p>
                The Put It Down app was created and designed to help users deter themselves
                from picking up or using their smartphone while driving.
            </p><br />
            <h3>How it works:</h3><br />
            <ol style="list-style-type: lower-roman;">
                <li>Open the app</li>
                <li>New Drive</li>
                <li>Rest phone somewhere relatively flat and where it won't move much</li>
                <li>Press Begin Drive</li>
                <li>Begin Driving</li>
            </ol><br />
            <p>
                The phone checks the angle of the phone each second against its angle the
                previous second. If the angle change is more than 30 degrees, it sounds
                an alert, vibrates the phone, and pins where the "pick-up" occurred in
                <span class="label label-default">MapKit</span>. At the end of the drive,
                the user may save the drive which then gets stored in the iPhone's <span class="label label-default">CoreData</span> for later retrieval.
            </p>
